          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><h1 id=\"3-compare-speed-of-rnn-implementations\">3 - Compare speed of RNN implementations</h1></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "pHFh",
      "code_hash": "2090769086f0bff2d1d88c286ea5bc70",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">Now we will do a simple comparison of the speeds of both RNN implementations, using 'tqdm'.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">tqdm creates a handy progress bar, and also tells you the amount of time per iteration it takes to complete a for loop.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "NCOB",
      "code_hash": "b375665e1fb3fb35c211515303150e19",
      "outputs": [],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "aqbW",
      "code_hash": "38d87e84497e721f633c9be66b26ad08",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">You should see a progress bar, then a number followed by either 'it/s' or by 's/it'</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">'it/s' means the number of iterations of the for-loop completed per second, as 's/it' means the number of seconds taken to complete a single iteration of the for loop.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">For the above, with the PyTorch RNN, it should be completing around 1 s/it. That means it processes an entire batch of ten 10000 length inputs, then backpropagates the loss through this in about one second.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">Now compare this with the custom implementation:</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "TRpd",
      "code_hash": "b81f1fddc8e152bffd1565d5ef4cdd31",
      "outputs": [],
      "console": []
    },
    {
      "id": "TXez",
      "code_hash": "5d7264581df8a8c4295d27a86331a145",
      "outputs": [
        {
          "type": "data",
          "data": {
            "text/markdown": "<span class=\"markdown prose dark:prose-invert contents\"><span class=\"paragraph\">This should take about 3 second per iteration. Much slower!</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">A major reason for this is that when PyTorch does calculations, it actually calls a C++ library called 'torch' to do the maths. When using the PyTorch RNN class, PyTorch passes the entire sequence of inputs to the underlying C++ function.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">In the myRNN library, the C++ torch library is still being called to calculate the linear layer outputs, but now it is being called once every time-step in the input sequence! There is some overhead everytime Python calls C++, so this results in it being much slower compared to the PyTorch RNN, which only has to call the C++ library once for the entire sequence.</span>\n<span class=\"paragraph\">To create your own custom PyTorch modules that include recursions (like the RNN), implementing the recursion in C++ will greatly improve processing speed.</span></span>"
          }
        }
      ],
      "console": []
    },
